actices on completing campaign and event briefs. It was great to talk through examples, discuss where there are challenges, and think about solutions to help streamline the process while also providing our colleagues with the information they need to create and launch programs. Your commitment to helping us all be better at this is much appreciated!\n\n348#Webinar Fire Drill|Thank you all so much for your help with the webinar fire drill on Friday! Jay, we could never have gotten the follow-up emails out if you hadn‚Äôt come to the rescue. Thank you for putting the breaks on everything so you could get the video up online. And thank you for all the troubleshooting! Diane, as always, you pulled out all the stops to get the thing done! You have the patience of a saint, and so much fortitude. Thanks to you we were able to get the webinar follow-up emails, and tasks assigned by EOD. And Jill, thank you for all your help with the reporting. It was a jumbled mess, and I‚Äôm so grateful for your help in sorting it all out. Nothing about this situation was ideal but everyone pulled together to make what could have been a much worse situation, so much better. Thank you all!\n\n349#Keeping it real!|Jill, just wanted to thank you for giving me some great feedback on a work-in-progress 'video / animation' project brief we've been working on. You've set aside time from your busy schedule to collaborate with our team on this, sitting down with me and emailing me your valuable opinions from a non-video perspective, and some really thoughtful suggestions along the way. User testing and refinement based on first impressions and open feedback is a major key to what we do every day, thanks for keeping it real and being so helpful!\n\n350#Teamwork makes the dreamwork|Thank you both for finding the time on such short notice, to record the extra 15 minutes of Q&A for our webinar replay with HR.com! I‚Äôm sure we‚Äôll get MANY more registrations now that we meet the minimum time criteria 